6. Chain API calls — use value from response A in request B
No flags needed. Use I extract and {alias} placeholders:


Scenario: Resolve venue then fetch its logs
  When I send a "GET" request to "/api/StpFix/Status"
  Then the response HTTP status should be 200
  And I extract "venueName" from the response and store as "venue"

  # {venue} is replaced at runtime with the extracted value
  When I send a "GET" request to "/api/StpFix/fixLogs?venue={venue}&logType=bj"
  Then the response HTTP status should be 200

mvn test -pl application-tests -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@chain" -Denv=qa
7. JSON Schema validation
Step 1 — Place your schema file under:


application-tests/src/test/resources/schemas/my-response-schema.json
Step 2 — Add the step to your scenario:


Then the response should conform to schema "my-response-schema.json"
Step 3 — Enable schema validation at run time (off by default so pipelines stay fast):


mvn test -pl application-tests \
  -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@schema" \
  -Denv=qa \
  -Dschema_validation=true
Without the flag the step is silently skipped — the scenario still passes.

8. Performance / SLA assertions
Add the step to any scenario:


When I send a "GET" request to "/api/StpFix/Status"
Then the response HTTP status should be 200
And the response time should be under 500 milliseconds
Enable at run time (off by default):


mvn test -pl application-tests \
  -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@perf" \
  -Denv=qa \
  -Dperf_testing=true
9. Windows / NTLM authentication (for corporate APIs)
Pass credentials as system properties — no code changes required:


mvn test -pl application-tests \
  -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@stp" \
  -Denv=qa \
  -Dstp.ntlm.username="DOMAIN\yourusername" \
  -Dstp.ntlm.password="yourpassword" \
  -Dstp.ntlm.domain="YOURDOMAIN"
Or set environment variables instead of system properties:


export STP_NTLM_USERNAME="DOMAIN\yourusername"
export STP_NTLM_PASSWORD="yourpassword"
export STP_NTLM_DOMAIN="YOURDOMAIN"

mvn test -pl application-tests -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@stp" -Denv=qa
